This quote from the lovely Meaghan Markle has really stuck with me: “I resolve not to have any resolutions…. the only thing I aim to do is to approach life playfully. To laugh and enjoy, to keep my standards high but my level of self-acceptance higher. My New Years resolution is to leave room for magic. To make my plans, and be okay if they sometimes break. To set my goals, but to be open to change. ⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀
.⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀
And I'd say this goal worked out well for Meaghan! ⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀
.⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀
Every single day, I'm working to improve myself - whether that's accepting the softness of my stomach or trying to use my phone less. But that doesn't mean there's something wrong with me. I don't need fixing. And nor do you. Because, as the very wise and wonderful Sophia Bush once said: "You are allowed to be both a masterpiece and work in progress simultaneously". ⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀
⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀
You can accept and love yourself in your current state, while still working to become the best version of yourself. In fact, you're actually even MORE likely to stick to your goals when you're doing it from this place of love, rather than fear. ⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀
⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀
Whatever you're thinking for a new years resolution - if that's your jam - make it kind. You deserve kindness.

Some important holiday rules. I’ll also add... Don’t let guilt ruin your holiday. And if someone close to you feels the need to comment on your weight or body, make sure you read my blog post about how to make it stop (click the link in my profile or go to www.lyndicohen.com)... .
Also... This is something I shared on Back to Basics today, but I want you to know it too. .
.
You may gain weight over the holiday. It’s natural. It happens. It’s nothing to worry about. When the holiday is over, you’ll naturally crave lighter food and more movement.
.
Your body will return to it’s pre-holiday weight when you return to your pre-holiday routine. Guilt won’t help eat less or lose weight. It messes with your happiness, isolates you from the people you love and ruins what is meant to be a happy time.
.
What's more, guilt doesn’t help you eat healthier. It sets you up for all-or-nothing thinking which leads to under-eating, followed by out-of control overeating.
.
The holidays are a time to relax around food. In fact, the holidays can help you learn to eat healthier. Instead of eating 'by the clock' (i.e. because it's lunch time), listening to your hunger. Wake up and wait to feel hungry to eat. Become curious about your natural hunger cues throughout the day. You might find you don't get hungry until 10am so simply practice waiting for hunger to eat. If you have a big lunch, you may not be hungry for dinner and that's fine too. Maybe a pot of yoghurt before bed is all you feel like.
.
In other words, swap guilt for curiosity and give yourself permission to eat or not eat according to your hunger. Give yourself the gift of a guilt-free holiday. .
.

If you need a last minute Christmas present for a special lady (or a lovely gent...!) check out my book The Nude Nutritionist. It's a brilliantly smart gift to give because it's 100% free from wellness wankery. It's perfect for your sister, mum, aunty, your best friend or Jacqui from work who's been on at least 147 diets in the past month alone... and who will NOT. stop. talking. about. it!!! (No one cares Jacqui!). ⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀
⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀
But really - It's a great gift because it's not just another health book (you know the type of talking about)... I'd rather shave off my left eyebrows or lick a squirrel than promote restriction or obsession to anyone. So you bet this book is diet free (thank goodness) and will also help you with self-acceptance - which makes it a great gift or purchase for yourself. Hooray! Plus, it's affordable too... ⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀
⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀
Instead of telling you what to eat every nanosecond of the day (meal plans aren't sustainable!), it's a friendly guide to get you off the never-ending yo-yo diet path that leads nowhere... except to the pantry to dig a dessert spoon directly into the peanut butter jar or the Milo tin. ⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀
⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀
Instead, The Nude Nutritionist will gently lead you toward living a healthier life that is actually doable because it's simple and involves absolutely no obsessing over food - because who the heck has time to count out almonds or track everything they eat? Plus, it's got 50+ delicious recipes, and worksheets. Check the link in my bio to grab a copy... Or go to Big W, Myer, David Jones, Booktopia, Dymocks, Book Depository, Amazon and any other place where good books are sold to get a copy. ⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀
⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀

What do you do if your mum won’t stop commenting on your weight? How do you get her (or anyone who makes judgemental comments) to stop criticising what you eat or your body? I know many of you will be spending more time with your family over the holidays - and these hurtful comments can be triggering. You don’t deserve to have a body bully in your life, and it especially shouldn’t be from someone as close as your mother. .
.
So if you need guidance on how to make the comments and judgement stop, I wrote a blog post that can help (you can click the link in my profile or go to www.lyndicohen.com to read it). I give a step by step approach and examples of things you can say... (of course, make it your own) because it can be a hard conversation to have. .
.
Check it out and let me know what you think. I’m trying to write blog posts more in case they help you but they take me a long time to write because I like to be thorough so please let me know what you think. 🙏❤️

"Pull in your tummy". I was told this a lot growing up. I'd try to keep my stomach pulled in or wear tight clothes to try to hold it all in... but then I'd get stomach cramps and feel deeply uncomfortable. Did this happen to you as well? For me, I'd constantly feel the need to adjust my top so it didn't sit tightly over my stomach. That was then... ⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀
Now I've realised that you're not meant to walk around with your tummy sucked in. It's unhealthy and uncomfortable. A healthy stomach doesn't need to be perfectly flat. What's more, pulling in your tummy doesn't allow you to properly rest and digest. Thanks to @amyg_yoga from @selphhealth for this life lesson. Having a comfortable, upright posture is important but all this sucking in because we hate that natural curve of our female stomach is craziness. ⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀
You see - I've always had this soft layer of fat that sits comfortably on top of my abdominal muscles. It's meant to be that way for my body shape. Truth is, few people have naturally plank-flat stomachs without going to extreme measures to get it. ⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀
I used to resent my tummy's slight protrusion but now I know that it's protecting me. This lovely layer of fat helps my body regulate my temperature so that I'm not cold all the time. It helps keep my hormones regulated.⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀
⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀
When I was at my thinnest, people would comment that I looked so good but they didn't really know that I wasn't eating enough, I was over-exercising and I was constantly cold and low in energy. The point is... Our idea of what a healthy body looks like is dead wrong (and commenting on peoples weight is always wrong). ⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀
⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀
So now that I know all this, I've learned to feel some affection for my little pooch, my tummy curve, my lovely lady lumps. And I'm a lot healthier for accepting it. The truth is I now have a lot more time and headspace to focus on real health goals.
.
P.s. if you’re a parent wondering if you should tell your daughter to ‘pull in her tummy’ or comment on her weight, please read my latest blog post (link in my profile or www.lyndicohen.com) xxx

Truthfully? I got annihilated by this year... it was a tough one. I moved back to Australia. I lost my dad to cancer. My husband's grandma passed away. We bought a house (and got a mortgage). I also wrote a book and created Back to Basics and I kept plugging away, and then sometimes I couldn't plug away anymore and I went quiet and I hid from the world for a bit and that was OK too because I was grieving and still am. I'd cry in the car, or in the shower and or in bed and I still do sometimes because losing something so important to you leaves a deep hole. I realise that no happy occasion will ever be free from the sadness of my dad not being there. But still... Storms make a tree lay it’s roots deeper so it becomes more grounded and the same has happened for me. This hard, brutal year has made me more robust and strong and driven. I'm almost 30 and I can feel I'm being shaped to be the person I'm meant to be. I'm more grateful than ever - to be alive, for a body that functions so well without my telling it how. And I'm grateful to be able to do work that I feel is so deeply important... and to exist in a really fake influencer world as a very real person and to be seen (really, truly seen for who I am) thanks to like-minded, sincere people like you. I end this year more hopeful and stronger than ever. Whatever your year looked like, my friend, I hope next year is a bright one for all of us.

Consistency - not perfection is what gets you healthy (and keeps you healthy). ⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀.⠀⠀⠀
Done in real life is ALWAYS better than a perfect plan that never ends up happening. Small movement really does add up to big results. And if choosing gentler exercise (like a walk over a run) means you'll enjoy it and be more likely to do it - then forget calories. THAT is the healthiest exercise for YOU.⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀
.⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀
Exercise should not feel like punishment for eating... And it should be enjoyable. Otherwise, you're doing it wrong. ⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀
.⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀

Last year I made a New Years resolution. It was simple. *Be kind to myself*. But like... exceptionally kind. Cause I used to be pretty good at beating myself up. I’d lie in bed at night for hours running over all the ways I’ve ever failed (there are lots) but neglect all the ways I’d done good.
.
This New Years resolution meant forgiving myself when things didn’t go perfectly and... also accepting that I don’t need to look perfect from every angle. It was a major turning point for me. You may notice that I’m now someone who is really comfortable in her skin. You can’t fake that kinda thing and I want you to also wake up feeling happy to be you. 🥰
.
So I noted down everything I did to change how I see myself, how I treat myself and how I talk to myself... and I’ve stuffed it into a big blog post. You can go read it via the link in my profile or at www.lyndicohen.com. Learning to be kind to myself may have been the best thing I’ve ever done for myself ❤️. .
.
Please go read the post and then come back and share your thoughts. It would be great to know someone other than my mum reads my blog. 😂

This is a topic close to heart. Research shows commenting on your daughter (or sons) weight leaves them worse off. And I think I’m proof of that. Swipe right to see images of me before I started getting weight based comments and a photo from after, following many years of trying to be thin enough to make those comments stop. You can see my weight change from these photos but what you can’t see is how much pain those well-intentioned but ultimately harmful comments had. .
I’ve written a blog post about How to talk to your daughter about their weight... and it’s an important one. You can read it via the link in my profile, via my stories or at www.lyndicohen.com ❤️ plus, I also have practical ideas to help your kids be healthy without giving them a complex about their weight. Please go have a read and share with parents or future parents. .
.
Today, I got to speak to my amazing little cousin Millie’s entire Kingergarten class about healthy eating (see the third pic!). And they’re so keen to eat the rainbow - and it breaks my heart to think they any of them would one day diet. It’s sad to think that little girls become aware that being thin is desired from the age of 6! And while parents talk to little boys about growing muscles, they caution little girls about gaining weight. That’s why I wrote this post specifically for our little girls - but mostly I wrote it for any adult who is a parent, Aunty, uncle, big cousin, teacher or friend to a little one. .
Also, you’ll also see a photo of me holding my vibrant, amazing niece Luna 🐛 and my incredible little Evie Hawkins @kathrynhawkins_ @kaminanicole 🙏 All these little girls have such great role models 💕 .
.

These are some of my favourite sources of plant-based protein. In this image, I’ve listed the amount of protein you get from an average serve when it’s ready-to-eat (i.e cooked, soaked). That’s because comparing raw vs cooked foods or comparing by 100g serves doesn’t make sense when you don’t eat raw quinoa or you don’t eat 100g of peanut butter (although… 😏🥄). Also - FYI 100g of beans is about half a tin, drained. Tag a friend who could benefit from seeing this or save it to refer to later. .
.
Another idea to keep in mind. Combining different plant-based foods can help you get to your protein goals. (AD) For example, making a salad with 125g of @Sunrice Supergrains with half a tin of beans will give you almost 10g of plant protein. Add a handful of nuts for another 5g of protein. Add in a mix of your favourite vegetables for protein-rich, fibre loaded and delicious meal. You’ll also get plenty of plant diversity in this meal, which is great for gut microbiota (we should aim to get 30 different types of plant-based foods in our diet per week for a healthy gut). .
.
I’m not a vegetarian though I am currently trying to eat less meat. I’ve written a juicy blog post with all my tips. Click the link in my profile to read it or go to www.lyndicohen.com

To my dear nutrition colleagues. Your clients and patients will come to you desperate to be made thinner - imagining that their lives will be infinitely better if they just weigh less. .
.
At times like this, remember: It's not your job to make people the thinnest version of themselves. You can do SO much more for them.
.
Hear them (with bucketloads of empathy) when they tell you how they hate their soft tummy that's never quite flat - or how they've spent years trying to weigh less. .
.
Then when they're ready, gently explain the beautiful, awesome truth that is: Their body has their back!! And if they simply redirect their energy away from focusing on their weight - and put that glorious energy into adopting truly healthy habits bit by bit - their body will naturally find it's sweet spot. .
.
Remind them their body wants them to be a healthy weight for them - wherever that healthy weight is. Remind them that real health takes time. And let them know that it’s time to finally stop fighting their body - and instead, learn to sit back and listen 🙌. .
.
Give them permission to know it's time to stop recording everything they eat in an app (as though it can measure their worth when it sure as hell can't). Tell them it’s OK - and beneficial - to stop counting macros and cutting out whole food groups. And help them (one healthy habit at a time) become the healthiest, best, happiest versions of themselves. Always remember that THIS is the real work that you're here to do.

#nutritionist #nutrition #dietitian #rd #apd #hcp #fitnessprofressional #realhealth #healthyweight #bodygoals #realtalk #nutritiongoals #dietitiansofinstagram #dietitiansunite

I started dieting at 11 years old. 😢 And so started a decade long war with my body and food... I’d lose weight and then regain it - each time gaining more than I’d previously lost. You see, I was actually really good at losing weight. I knew the rules! I could play the game but I could never. keep. the. weight. off. .
.
And I became so ridiculously angry with myself for not having better willpower. And so damn desperate!! Because I was either obsessing about food and ‘being really good’ or eating ice-cream and peanut butter by the spoonfuls from the jar. There was no in/between. 😔 I hated my body no matter what size I was. .
.
At my heaviest, I was so very desperate to lose weight (again) but... I looked back at the years I spent trying the exact same approach and realised that if I wanted a different outcome, I had to do things differently. So Instead of signing up for another diet program (that was camouflaged as a “healthy lifestyle approach”) or listening to the nutrition noise - I got back to basics and listened to my body, instead of food rules. And I got my life back. Health became something that made my life better - not controlled it. .
.
This isn’t a story about weight loss... it’s my life experience so far and it’s why I do what I do and why the diet industry and wellness world make me so angry. I’ve made this my job because I want to prevent this kinda story from happening for you. .
.
You better believe that as a nutritionist - I’m not here to help you be the thinnest version of yourself. Thats shit and you deserve more. Here’s what I learned. You don’t need to eat perfectly or sacrifice 95% of your life to weigh 5% less. You can feel comfortable in your body and have plenty of energy and not be obsessed with your weight or body fat percentage. Everything I do in my work - whether it’s on social media or in Back to Basics - is done to help you be healthy but without comprising your wellness. .
.
Thanks for allowing me to turn up in your feed and do this work. I’m glad you know why I do this work. And I think it’s always good to know that even if you’ve been dieting for years, you can learn a new way of thinking about food. ❤️🙌

Yesterday, I learned that this is not how you hold a golf club. 
I also learned that it’s seriously great for your mental health to get outside and play a sport and do something different away from your phone. ☀️🍃 Exercise doesn’t have to be in the gym or in Lemons that are lulu. I wore my golf-iest outfit (see plaid pants, sweet little hat... though I totally think I’m missing a polo shirt for the full look 🏌️‍♀️). I had a lesson and lunch at @mooreparkgolf... I’d go back just to eat another cauliflower salad and to sit with a beer overlooking the trees because that was all kinds of nice... I also had a lesson with @aussiebeefgolf who turned out to be a really great teacher (how’s my swing?!) and good guy but he also doesn’t think golf should be stuffy or pretentious and I really do agree. .
.
Thanks for having me @mooreparkgolf - it was a mighty good way to hang with friends, enjoy fresh air and move my body. Not going to lie - I’m stiff in muscles I never knew lived in my body 😎 .
.
P.s. I know dads and brothers and partners (and girl friends and sisters too!) can be tricky to buy presents for. I really think a golf lesson is a ripping good Chrissy present. Our couples lesson with @aussiebeefgolf was epic 🍃🏌️‍♀️☀️🏌️‍♂️😎@sydgolfacademy  #sydneygolflessons

This is important. Lemon water does not (in any way) detox your body. There is zero evidence to suggest lemon water detoxes anything. 🍋 Your body can regulate it’s own pH. Your body can detox itself otherwise you’d be dead. And your teeth will become eroded if you get sucked into believing this wide spread nutrition myth. .
.
If you are a well intentioned Heath influencer, please don’t encourage people to sip on lemon water. The first part of health work is to do no harm. It’s bad advice. Dentists around the world will thank you. And so will the people you seek to help. 🙏❤️ .
.
If you insist on having lemon water, then I recommend drinking it from a reusable straw to bypass your teeth ☺️🍋💦 .
#nutritionmyth #nutribollocks #lemonwater #detox #dietitian #nutritionist #healthadvice #backtobasics

What you think people look like according to Instagram VS how people really look when they accidentally swipe up into their camera. 😂🔥
.
This happened today so I had to take a photo of my sweet mug and double chin as further proof to the warped standards we demand of ourselves. .
.
You cannot look great from every angle. That is not your job in life. You have much more important things to think about. When you have a bad body image day, accept that it’s simply fact that you won’t look awesome every freaking day. Its no fault of your own and you should remind yourself of this and keep on with you day. We are all imperfect. That’s life! 
#instagramvsreality
